recordings.rmk: As well as drumming and (at the end of the clip) a flight call from a Great Spotted Woodpecker, other species are nicely recorded in the sequence.  Here is the list: GREAT SPOTTED WOODPECKER drums seven times. Note how the resonance of some drums change, especially the final two - because the bird moves to a different piece of tree trunk. The woodpecker can also be heard tapping [0:57] and then it flies a short distance, giving its rather manic 'roving' call as it does so [1:33]. CHIFFCHAFF sings at 0:07, 0:16, 0:23.  CHAFFINCH sings at 0:28, 0:37 and a few more times. WILLOW WARBLER sings at 0:31 and 1:02. LONG-TAILED TIT calls from 0:44 until the 55th second. BLACKCAP sings at 0:57, 1:05, 1:11, 1:16, 1:26 and 1:31. DUNNOCK sings at 1:20.  Also in the background - Wren, Moorhen (one call) and Woodpigeon.

Centre of the territory is a group of eight poplars in a coniferous forest (pine and larch) with addition of birches and willows. In poplars two hollows can be found. One male and two-three femals are observed in the territory. One of the females is a territorial female, she is accepted by the male (drumming and defending territory together).

The female drums on a dry branch of willow (Salix caprea). After a while calls of three other birds can be heard from different directions. 
0:17.1 – from the direction of Great Spotted Woodpecker pair’s territory described before, from the distance of around 150 meters female arrives, calling. 
0:18.7 – answer of the drumming female. After some time birds fly away into the woods.

recordings.rmk:
Recordings (XC351729, XC351730, XC351731, XC352238, XC352369, XC352430, XC352433,XC352434, XC352436, XC352438, XC352439, XC354837, XC354838, XC354839, XC354840, XC354841, XC354842, XC354843) made in the winter territory of Great Spotted Woodpecker pair. Centre of the territory is a group of eight poplars in a coniferous forest (pine and larch) with addition of birches and willows. In poplars two hollows can be found. One male and two-three femals are observed in the territory. One of the females is a territorial female, she is accepted by the male (drumming and defending territory together).

0:01 – Intruder female drums on a dry, thin poplar branch.
0:47.0  – territorial female comes from the distance of around 60 meters.  After a while she sits on the same poplar and drums on a dry, broken branch which is used most often. At the same time intruder female remains quiet, still and motionless. Eventually at 1:36.0 she answers with a quiet drumming. Territorial female immediately flies to the top of next poplar and observes nearby trees, attempting to localize the intruder. The intruder female remains still and hidden for next 30 seconds. Finally at 2:14.5 drums on a dry branch. Territorial female in the same moment spots her and drives her far away.
